CLASSIFICATION_COM: The epithet is sometimes corrected to "muhlenbergii", reflecting the fact that Muhlenberg did not spell his name with an umlaut over the "u", nor did he use "ue". Willdenow, however (as well as Schkuhr) was German, and his use of the umlaut should be assumed to represent what he considered the correct German spelling of the name. It therefore should not be considered an error and is not correctable under the Melbourn Code.

This taxon should not be confused with H. pauciflora (= Anthoxanthum arcticum), a boreal species that does not reach the U.S. The epithets "arcticum" and "arctica" in these names have different basionyms. See also taxonomic comments under Hierochloe odorata.

This name has was formerly used by us (and currently by the PA Flora Project) in a more broad sense to include H. hirta, which we currently track as H. hirta ssp. arctica. H. odorata in the strict sense has a coastal distribution in North America, extending from Labrodor to Delaware. The specimen from Wayne Co.at CM should be examined. For the time being we are transferring the EO to H. hirta ssp. arctica, with ID=?.

CLASSIFICATION_COM: Porteranthus is a superfluous replacement name for Gillenia, which is not a homonym of Gillena Adans (S. Grund, personal communication, 2015-12-08).
S_DISTRIBUTION_COM: The supposed painting of G. stipulata in Jennings and Avinoff is clearly Gillenia trifoliata. The specimen used as a model for the painting is not at Carnegie Museum (CM), and may have been lost in a flood. Porter (1903) cites Allegheny County, and this is probably based on the same material as reports in various manuals, going back at least to the 5th edition of Gray's Manual (Gray 1867). No Pennsylvania specimen of this species was found at Harvard University Herbaria (HUH), in either the G. stipulata folder or the G. trifoliata folder. A Distribution Confidence of either R or PRF could be applied, as there is a false report, but also unconfirmed reports. SW Pennsylvania would be a reasonable range extension. All specimens in the Pennsylvania G. trifoliata folders at CM were checked by Grund in 2015; none are G. stipulata (S. Grund, personal communication, 2015-10-08).
